column11: Adaptation of the Informedb Enterprise web application for the USMC Modernization Master Plan (MMP)

Two issues need to be addressed with this item (from Release 1 Known Issues):

- No visual feedback is given when a PoR or Development Effort save is initiated. If a user edits a field in a PoR or Development Effort form while it is saving, it will be overwritten by the saved version once the update is complete. Wait for feedback indicating the save is complete before changing data fields.

- Navigating between tabs in the PoR or Development Effort details pages while a save is occurring puts the rich text editors in an unusable state. Wait for feedback indicating the save is complete before changing tabs.

column1: Connections View
column11: Adaptation of the Informedb Enterprise web application for the USMC Modernization Master Plan (MMP)
column28:
Acceptance Criteria:
-	A user can view what program of records are related to the development effort viewed
-	A user can view what roadmaps are related to the development effort viewed
-	A user can view what funding increments are related to the development effort viewed
o	Funding increments are not related to programs of record or roadmaps
-	A user can view what development efforts are related to the Program of Record viewed
-	A user can view what roadmaps are related to the Program of Record viewed
-	Can navigate to the details of related items

Description:
Contract:

6. D3 View:  Quick connectivity view of what each object is connected to

Story:
As an ATI, I want to know what a program of record or development effort is related to so that I can answer a data call or identify potential problems with it

Implementation Notes (Initial):
- Overview-type map for finding out what is connected to what
- Need to find a place in this site for this to fit.
- Start with relationships between roadmaps, dev efforts, and program of record
- Investigate to see whether or not other data would be helpful (like funding).

Implementation Notes From Feature Shaping 11/9/2020:
- Something in the details page
- Clearly differentiate kinds of things (roadmaps vs. development effort)
- It would be really neat to see the details of the things in the (chart, view)
- Really useful information in the data: 
-- Development efforts: Name, PM, funding source, status
-- Program of record: Name, PM, acronym
-- Roadmap: Name, PM, image
-- Funding increment: type and total

Notes:
I don’t know if a dev effort is connected to a roadmap
Provide the user an understanding of what “that thing” is connected to”
Dev effort is connected to this program of record, roadmap, funding elements
-	Finding if there’s no program of record it’s connected to
-	Show TRL at transition point (bonus)
What flavor of money is getting them to a transition point?
Program of record =>
  What dev efforts feed into it, what roadmaps it is a part of
Should we approach the tabs differently?
Development effort a specific set of kinds of funding
Transitioning => level of maturity is high, globally agreed it is needed. Lots of $$$
Gap analysis – am I missing funding, is it not going to be mature enough
Could be really easy to put in other places if we componentize it right
column72:
14/Jan/21 11:52 AM;MattChild;As discussed on 2020-11-30, the connections tab idea was agreed as a good starting point. For MVP, we need to:

    Clearly identify what is a program of record vs roadmap vs dev effort
    We should not make anything selectable (until we can add some other features to make selection more useful).

column1: Notify what other roadmaps will be affected when moving a roadmap's milestones
column11: Adaptation of the Informedb Enterprise web application for the USMC Modernization Master Plan (MMP)
column28:
When user's move milestone dates from a Program of Record or Development Effort on a roadmap, if that Program of Record or Dev Effort is on another Roadmap, that roadmap will also be affected. On the whole, this is a good thing because it allows them to manage schedule for programs or dev efforts that have far reaching impacts. However, a user may accidentally make a change that will have more impacts than they're aware of, without realizing it. This has become even more likely to happen with the "Clone" feature, which users may try to use as a "What-if" and accidentally modify the original (even with all the special instructions we included around this case).

It would be helpful to give some sort of indication about the number of roadmaps that have been (or will be) affected by a change so that a user will have a clear understanding of the implications of the change.

column1: Cloning the same item twice allows violation of the unique name constraint
column11: Adaptation of the Informedb Enterprise web application for the USMC Modernization Master Plan (MMP)
column28:
If the user clones an item, and the default copy name of <Object Name> Copy already exists, another record is created with that name, violating the unique name constraint that is in place for standard creation.

NOTE: The acceptance criteria uses a Copy (1)...(2)... etc. scheme, similar to browser downloads and multiple file rename in Windows, so it's a standard scheme that our users should be accustomed to.
column46: - If the default clone name is unavailable when the user requests to clone an object, attempt to use <Object Name> Copy (1) instead, then (2)...(3)...etc.
column72: 22/Oct/20 4:45 PM;ScottSummerford;This may be difficult to do, as the current foundation for cloning objects relies on using the InformedbAPI. I thought that it had precautions for handling this, but evidently not.

column1: Roadmaps - Multiple DevEfforts with the same position breaks chart
column11: Adaptation of the Informedb Enterprise web application for the USMC Modernization Master Plan (MMP)
column28:
On a roadmaps chart it's possible to have multiple nodes overlap. When this happens, you can normally click on them to see the list of nodes / names on the left hand side.

If you try to create a link on overlapping nodes, normally it'd open a popup menu to tell you to select one from the list. This works for POR, but does not for Development Efforts.

This is because the schedules for Development Efforts have no unique identifiers. If you have two schedule entries with the same quarter / year / type, there's no distinction besides their GUID, which the user does not know.

 

How should the options for this popup menu be displayed if there are no names? "Node 1, Node 2... etc"?. A List of their guids? This is an existing MMPv1 behavior so we've paused it for 2.0

column1: Removing Project Access and then changing to that project causes a page dump
column11: Adaptation of the Informedb Enterprise web application for the USMC Modernization Master Plan (MMP)
column28:
On the user management page, you can remove access to a project and then immediately try to change to it.

column1: Removing Self from Current Project can cause errors
column11: Adaptation of the Informedb Enterprise web application for the USMC Modernization Master Plan (MMP)
column28:
If you remove yourself from the project you're currently on, and then allow yourself to time out (occasionally logging out immediately can do this as well), you can get into an error state where you are unable to login (account locked error) and the user management page bugs out for everyone (options are null),

 

This occurs because you circumvent the checks that would reassign you to a new project to replace the one you don't have access to.

It should be pretty rare, but would be pretty nasty if it occurs more frequently than expected.

column28:
As an MMP User, I want an easy way to understand which records are being deleted when I am about to do so.

Currently, the deletion prompt is a basic JavaScript alert box, which is not effective for communicating large lists of information. Create a modal dialog box with a scrollable list that can handle displaying the names of large lists of records.
column46:
- When deleting Programs, Dev Efforts, or Roadmaps via selection, a modal displays containing the list of names of the objects about to be deleted.
- The modal should not be taller than 1/3 to 1/2 of the screen.
- The list of names should be scrollable if it will cause the modal to break the height constraints.
- The modal should allow the user to confim or cancel the operation.
- The modal should update with success or failure for each listed item.
